      def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
          cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
          sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
          plt.ylabel('Observed')
          plt.xlabel('Predicted')
          plt.show()

      # Overall conclusion

      Overall conclusion¶

       
      The accuracy of all methods is quite good. As said, this is primarily caused by the very high number of True Negatives.
      ​
      However, when looking at recall and the f1 score (which are the most valuable number to focus on in this case), the Bagging algorithm seems to do the best job. 
      ​
      Furthermore, the number of true negatives is not our primary focus, the company can stil exclude those customers from the 
      population that is used for the campaign. 
      ​
      NOTE: changing the outliers of balance and campaign to the mean of both, didn't improve the recall.

      The accuracy of all methods is quite good. As said, this is primarily caused by the very high number of True Negatives.

      However, when looking at recall and the f1 score (which are the most valuable number to focus on in this case), the Bagging algorithm seems to do the best job.

      Furthermore, the number of true negatives is not our primary focus, the company can stil exclude those customers from the population that is used for the campaign.

      NOTE: changing the outliers of balance and campaign to the mean of both, didn't improve the recall.
